Use `.absolute()` instead of `.resolve()` for `VHDL_PATH` / `VERILOG_PATH`.

`.resolve()` follows symlinks. Under Bazel-sandboxed test actions,
the `vunit_hdl` package is staged into the action's runfiles tree as
a symlink pointing at the underlying `~/.cache/bazel/.../external/...`
cache. Resolving the symlink escapes the runfiles sandbox into a
location that is not part of the action's declared inputs;
sandboxing strategies that hide files outside the runfiles tree
(notably the linux processwrapper) then make the resolved path
unreadable from inside the action, breaking SV / VHDL builtin source
registration and the dep-scanner's include-path resolution.

`.absolute()` gives an absolute path WITHOUT following symlinks, so
the returned path stays inside the sandbox view (typically
`<runfiles>/+http_archive+vunit_hdl/vunit/{vhdl,verilog}` under
bzlmod). Native, non-Bazel installs of VUnit see no behaviour change
— the absolute form of a non-symlinked path matches its resolved
form.

A separate concern handled by the rules_vunit driver
(`tools/rules_vunit_run/rules_vunit_run.py:ensure_vunit_verilog_path_is_plus_free`):
Bazel's bzlmod external-repo prefix `+http_archive+...` contains
literal `+` characters, which Aldec vlog treats as list separators
in `+incdir+`/`+define+` arguments. The driver detects this and
stages the SV builtin tree to a `+`-free location, then rebinds
`VERILOG_PATH` to the staged copy before `add_verilog_builtins()`
runs. VHDL has no analogous `+`-separated CLI syntax, so VHDL_PATH
only needs the sandbox-escape fix here, not the `+`-staging.

Drop this patch when VUnit upstream switches to `.absolute()` (or a
sandbox-safe equivalent).

--- a/vunit/builtins.py
+++ b/vunit/builtins.py
@@ -20,7 +20,7 @@
 LOGGER = logging.getLogger(__name__)

-VHDL_PATH = (Path(__file__).parent / "vhdl").resolve()
-VERILOG_PATH = (Path(__file__).parent / "verilog").resolve()
+VHDL_PATH = (Path(__file__).parent / "vhdl").absolute()
+VERILOG_PATH = (Path(__file__).parent / "verilog").absolute()


 class Builtins(object):
